            <div type="commentary">
                <p><!--commented out pending revision-->
                    <!--Wilson , caption to fig.130 comments: 'Sphaeristeria are first mentioned on inscriptions from Delos and Delphi in the C3 BC, when they refer to rooms in gymnasia set aside for ball-play, but under the Empire, with the decline of the gymnasium as a separate institution and the absorption of many of its features by the bath-house, the sphaeristerium was more generally to be sought in the public baths. Because this stone was found not in situ, but just outside the town (no.9 on fig.129.7), where it had no doubt been re-used in post-Roman times, we do not know where the building at Centuripe to which it belonged was situated, nor whether the latter was of the bath-gymnasium type well known in Asia minor at Sardis, Ephesus and eslewhere, or (as is more likely) belonged to one of the bath-house types usually found in the West. Certainly sphaeristeria are attested on latin public inscriptions elsewhere in the West, at Nimes in southern France, and at Avenches in Switzerland, and they appear in private villas too - the younger Pliny's villas in Tuscany and near Rome both boasted one; so the Centuripe inscription cannot be taken to document the survival of gymnasia in imperial Sicily. Nor do we know whether the office of gymnasiarch there outlived the late Republic: unfortunately the date of a now-lost Greek inscription documenting a gymnasiarch at Centuripe (from the Acqua Amara baths, 3 on fig. 129.7) is unknown. (His name happens to be Cornelius, not necessarily of course, on of the pair recroded on the sphaeristerium inscription, or even a near contemporary.) Evidence for gymnasiarchs elsewhere in Sicily appears to be no later than the first century B.C. (see Fig.33 [his note on IG 14.311]), but the office is known to have survived durng the Empire in south Italian towns with a pronounced Greek character, for example at Velia, and such a survival in Sicily, while not so far definitely attested, would not be surprising. Probably first half of the second century AD. Grey marble, 61 cm long, 26 cm high. Palermo, museo archaeologico regionale'. [Roger is in fact basically cribbing ILLPa no.4 here, which latter has the ref. for the Greek inscr. - Ansaldi, G. 1851. I monumenti dell'antica Centuripe (Catania), 15-16]. For further refs. on sphaeristeria, see Wilson 1990, p.379 n.37. Libertini (1926) has a fairly similar sort of discussion p.75-6 on uncertainty of location/building, and connection or not with the lost gymnasiarch inscr. On Sphaeristeria, see Roux, BCH 1980: 134ff.--></p>
